      "name": "Steady-state hemolysis index validation — comparator link absent",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared against benchtop hemolysis measurements conducted under steady-state constant-speed conditions (3000 RPM, 5 L/min) using the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry. The experimental dataset is identified in project documentation as the 'Morrison-SS-2021 steady-state hemolysis corpus'. Mean NIH error across five impeller speeds was 8.3 %, which the assessment team characterises as acceptable agreement. However, the COU2 intended use explicitly requires pulsatile flow conditions representative of VAD cardiac-cycle loading (heart rate 60–100 bpm, stroke volume 50–90 mL). Steady-state conditions suppress the transient shear stress peaks that drive hemolysis in pulsatile regimes; the inference from steady-state agreement to pulsatile predictive credibility is therefore an undercutting mismatch (D3). The comparedAgainst link to the experimental reference dataset is not recorded in this result object, constituting the W-AR-05 trigger condition.",
      "validationMethod": "Direct comparison of CFD NIH to in-vitro NIH under steady-state constant-flow boundary conditions",
      "achievedMetric": "Mean NIH relative error 8.3 % across five operating points",
      "limitationNote": "Validation conducted under steady-state flow only; COU2 mandates pulsatile boundary conditions. Steady-state comparator does not bound pulsatile hemolysis error and is methodologically inappropriate for this COU."
